SB827/GTFSr Examples

Tom Buckley

3/3/2018

Senate Bill 827

The intent of Senate Bill 827 is to allow for more housing in areas of California with good transit.

Transit-Rich

Lets look at a specific recent amendment to the bill to understand how good is defined.

Within a 1/4 mile of a High Frequency Transit Stop

A recently proposed amendment to Senate Bill 827 says:

A project must be within mile of a transit stop on a high frequency transit corridor to trigger SB 827.

https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB827

So well need to be able to identify a few things in order to say whether a project triggers 827.

  1. transit stops
  2. transit corridors
  3. high frequency transit corridors

All of these have an intuitive definition, but we have to make assumptions in order to identify them.

SB 827 Features

So lets try to find the features in the world that correspond to (1), (2), and (3).

R Studio/GTFSr

Im going to use R Studio to get GTFS Transit Data and put it in maps and tables corresponding to (1), (2) and (3).

GTFS characterizes stops, routes, and schedules, among other things.

The top of this example is drawn from the introductory documents.

Getting Transit Data

TransitFeeds

TransitFeeds is a community edited site that lists transit data for tens of thousands of places around the world. Its awesome.

Theres an excellent introduction to pulling data for any city in TransitFeeds in the gtfsr documents here.

MTC 511

I found that, for the Bay Area, it made more sense to use MTCs 511 API.

Among other reasons, their list of operators is more comprehensive (see appendix).

library(readr)

#read 511 orgs list

Well use the PrivateCode to get data for a given operator.

Im going to use a list of URLs that I got from MTC 511.

So, lets get San Franciscos transit data.

Note that youll need an MTC511 API Key. You can get one here

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
operator_acronym <- filter(o511, Name == "SFMTA") %>% select(PrivateCode)

#Sys.setenv(APIKEY511 = "YOUR API KEY")
api_key = Sys.getenv("APIKEY511")

zip_request_url = paste0('http://api.511.org/transit/datafeeds?api_key=',
                           api_key,
                           '&operator_id=',
                           operator_acronym)

g1 <- zip_request_url %>% import_gtfs

(1) Transit Stops

This should be easy. A stop is discrete.

dim(g1$stops_df)[1]
## [1] 3536

Here we see there are 3k stops in SF Muni.

Lets look at a random sample of stops.

some_stops <- g1$stops_df[sample(nrow(g1$stops_df), 40),]

some_stops_sf <- stops_df_as_sf(some_stops)

mapview(some_stops_sf)

OK so seems like weve got (1).

What about (2)?

Transit Corridors

Since weve already identified some stops, lets get the routes those stops are on.

So how do we figure out which routes these stops are on?

We have to wade into the GTFS data model a bit to answer that question.

Thankfully, Danny Whalen made a chart which clarifies the data model:

So lets apply some dplyr verbs to get the routes for these stops.

some_stop_times <- g1$stop_times_df %>% 
    filter(stop_id %in% some_stops$stop_id) 

some_trips <- g1$trips_df %>%
  filter(trip_id %in% some_stop_times$trip_id)

some_routes <- g1$routes_df %>%
  filter(route_id %in% some_trips$route_id)

For these 100 stops, on this schedule there are 12k stops, 10k trips, and 48 routes.

Lets map these routes.

rts_sf <- gtfsr::routes_df_as_sf(g1)

some_routes_sf <- rts_sf %>% 
  filter(route_id %in% some_trips$route_id)

#in order to get mapview to display the routes
#had to save the data to a tempfile and read it back
tempfile1 <- tempfile("some_routes", fileext = ".gpkg")
st_write(some_routes_sf,tempfile1)
## Writing layer `some_routes10924442081e' to data source `/var/folders/hk/12t7fl6d08s7r494zd9sb8v40000gn/T//Rtmpxl3k6t/some_routes10924442081e.gpkg' using driver `GPKG'
## features:       42
## fields:         1
## geometry type:  Multi Line String

High Frequency

The next question is: how do we calculate frequency?

First, we also need to identify which calendar we are intersted in. In our case, weekdays.

c1 <- g1$calendar_attributes_df

weekday_service_id <- c1[c1$service_description=="Weekday",]$service_id

Lets try focusing on just 1 stop to see how this works.

a_stop_id <- some_stops_sf[1,]$stop_id

OK so now we have an idea of how we might get at high frequency stops.

stop_ids <- some_stops_sf[1:10,]$stop_id
# 
# headways <- sapply(stop_ids, function(x) stop_headway(x,g1$stop_times_df,
#                                                           g1$trips_df,
#                                                           weekday_service_id))

Lets try filtering for specific times of day.

stop_times_dt <- stop_times_df_as_dt(g1$stop_times_df)
library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date
am_start <- hms("06:00:00")
am_end <- hms("09:59:00")
pm_start <- hms("15:00:00")
pm_end <- hms("18:59:00")

peak_stop_times <- (stop_times_dt$departure_time > am_start &
                    stop_times_dt$departure_time < am_end) |
                    (stop_times_dt$departure_time > pm_start &
                    stop_times_dt$departure_time < pm_end)

#filter the df not dt frame here b/c of 
#bug where stop_times_dt$departure_times was not being filtered
stop_times_df <- g1$stop_times_df[peak_stop_times,]
stop_ids <- unique(stop_times_df$stop_id)

Appendix

MTC 511 API has more Operator coverage than TransitFeed

Compare coverage tables:

library(gtfsr)
library(sf)
feedlist_df <- get_feedlist() # create a data frame of all feeds

feedlist_sf = st_as_sf(feedlist_df, 
                       coords = c("loc_lng", "loc_lat"), 
                       crs = 4326)

counties <- st_read("https://data.sfgov.org/api/geospatial/s9wg-vcph?method=export&format=KML")
## Reading layer `Layer #0' from data source `https://data.sfgov.org/api/geospatial/s9wg-vcph?method=export&format=KML' using driver `KML'
## Simple feature collection with 9 features and 2 fields
## geometry type:  MULTIPOLYGON
## dimension:      XY
## bbox:           xmin: -123.5337 ymin: 36.89416 xmax: -121.2082 ymax: 38.86424
## epsg (SRID):    4326
## proj4string:    +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs
counties <- st_union(counties$geometry)[1]

counties <- st_sf(in_bay=c(1),geom=counties)

feedlist_sf <- st_join(counties,feedlist_sf, left=TRUE)
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
dim(feedlist_sf)
## [1] 31 10
feedlist_df <- dplyr::select(as.data.frame(feedlist_sf),-geom)
